<br>
Banana_Republic00 is in the midst of a civil war in which tens of thousands or innocent civilians are dying.<br>
<br>
Major_Power00 has to decide whether or not to get involved.  Major_Power00 has no stake in the civil war, neither outcome will harm it, none of its citizens are currently in danger, and there are Banana_Republic01 and Banana_Republic02 there that should be able to deal with it.<br>
<br>
If Major_Power00 intervenes, it risks the death of its own citizens, the loss of equipment and prestige, the costs of the operations, and the reduction in capability to deal with other situations that might arise which might be a more immediate threat to the interests of Major_Power00.<br>
<br>
Moreover, if Major_Power00 intervenes, International_Body00, which is dominated by the various Banana_Republics, will no doubt engage in major criticism of Major_Power00 for intervening in the sovereign affairs of Banana_Republic00, since it is in the interest of Banana_Republic01, 02 and 03 that 00 remains in turmoil, since they are profitting from the situation by looting the refugees.<br>
<br>
What is Major_Power00 supposed to do?<br>
<br>
Ethics and Morality are fine for personal behavior, but at the level of nation states, making decisions based on them can very well mean that your people will die.  Bush, Blair et al answer to their own nations people, not to Afghans or Palestinians, and if American or British soldiers are to be placed in harms way, it damn well better be for the benefit of America and the UK.<br>
<br>
Yes, I freely admit it is brutal, it is not 'nice', it is not 'fair', it is not 'kind'.  It is reality.  No nation, no matter how 'progressive', acts in anything other than its own self-interest.  If that self-interest happens to coincide with common morality, we call it 'enlightened self-interest'.   The United States acts that way, the UK acts that way, Canada acts that way, Switzerland acts that way, EVERY nation acts that way.<br>
<br>
In many ways diplomacy is the art of making other nations see that their self-interest lies with supporting your national self-interest.  When nations interests coincide, you have alliances, and oftentimes a nations interests are quite moral, witness the international relief efforts throughout the Third World, witness the major nuclear powers uniting to pressure India and Pakistan into backing down from the brink of nuclear war...<br>
<br>
Personal morality really doesn't enter into this equation at all, where morality makes its appearance is in the methods and procedures, not in the actual decisions.  After 9/11, the US could, with the full support of the US populace and the full understanding of nearly the entire world, have launched a few ICBM's at the known terrorist supporters strongholds and incinerated tens of millions of people along with the terrorists.  Or the US could engage in a pin-point precision campaign against the terrorists while simaltaneously engaging in humanitarian 'hearts and minds' operations.  The 'interests' of the US was to destroy terrorism, where morality came into play was in deciding that it was more moral to risk our own soldiers lives in direct combat with the enemy rather than make use of our massive nuclear arsenal to obliterate it.<br>
<br>
